    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 25,
    "last_activity_date" : 1303969536,
    "last_edit_date" : 1303969536,
    "creation_date" : 1303965674,
    "answer_id" : 5813698,
    "question_id" : 5813614,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>Error</code> and <code>Exception</code> both extend <code>Throwable</code>, but mostly <code>Error</code> is thrown by JVM in a scenario which is fatal and there is no way for the application program to recover from that error. For instance <code>OutOfMemoryError</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Though even application can raise an <code>Error</code> but its just not a good a practice, instead applications should use checked exceptions for recoverable conditions and runtime exceptions for programming errors.  </p>\n"
  } ],
